It’s not an exhaust but it sure is going to make it easy for me to build them!  I should have done this for myself ages ago it’s not a new idea, but better now than than never.  This is particularly useful for cad designed parts as I already have all of the instructions I need for cut angles and straight lengths.. I can create my own perfect Lego pieces for any job in full, completely ahead of the fabrication, instead of making them as you go which would otherwise be the procedure, and a waste of time. 
So this is made from 3d printed centers and a stainless laser etched and cut base, as well as stainless marker tabs.  Running a marker along the edge as it’s lined up is all it takes to get precise cutting instructions to the degree.  I also designed the little swing arms to be reversible, currently set up to the left side now for me as I’m left handed.  The stainless marker tab can slide a little bit on its arm which is useful for getting the tube in and out easily, those bolts are not tight, they’re just snug enough to allow the sliding and are locked there.  The base has 4 pins facing vertically that locate the blocks with a quick change layout, which is probably the best part about it; it takes nearly no time to switch what size tube I’m marking, and I’ll make all the center sizes I need over time.
Now I know people make and sell tools somewhat like this, some of which are super high quality, but you know I just like making my own stuff too sometimes, and I can make it however I want if it’s my design, I surely will continue to update and add features to this also.

The titanium Zpipe exhaust system is completed for SSC, as it was a customer option for their next Tuatara Striker hypercar.
What is a Zpipe?  It is surely not a bundle of tubes just to look cool, as this is not a styling exercise, though I have worked hard to keep her visually proportional.  The Zpipe creates a full mixture of exhaust gasses between both sides of the engine, giving a suction effect and creating a low pressure zone near the tips, literally pulling exhaust gasses out.  The side effect of this is an improved sound quality, as you’re hearing every pulse of the engine equally from each tip.

The Titanium Zpipe exhaust for @ssc_northamerica ‘s Tuatara Striker hypercar!! 
Tech talk time.  What is a Zpipe?  When a car has 2 exhaust tubes coming from the engine, those tubes are each split into 2, giving a total of 4 tubes.  From each side one tube is crossed over to the opposite side, and one tube stays on its own side, before combing back in to 2 total tubes, creating a forced 100% mixing of opposing sides.  This split and recombine approach invokes a strong scavenging effect, or a suction force, which allows every exhaust pulse to help pull the following pulse out from the opposite side, continuously going back and forth.  This low pressure zone effectively sucks exhaust out of the engine, kind of like a negative pressure supercharger.  Dyno proven to make more HP, yes I have even seen these gains on turbo applications despite the traditional  understanding of post turbo scavenging not existing.  For those who oppose this view of pulses existing post turbo, yes we can agree they are weakened, but if they were completely gone couldn’t we agree you would not even hear an exhaust note anymore?? Turbos lengthen the pulses, due to the variable distance around the turbine housing, but they do not remove them…. Let’s not also forget about the essentially “supercharged” exhaust pulses that come from the recirculating wastegates, often overlooked and capable of generating power as well.  Unfortunately I do not currently have the Dyno data for straight pipes vs Zpipe on this tuatara, however, I did test straight pipes vs Zpipe on a Ferrari 488 (also a twin turbo flat plane crank v8) and found a 32whp gain compared to straight pipes!  Look back about 3.5 years to find this post.. It had a similarly “excessive” amount of tubing added in comparison to straight pipes just like this tuatara system, and even with all this extra resistance it still more than made up for it with the suction effect given by the Zpipe.  Also let’s not forget, it makes every engine it gets attached to sound WAY better in my opinion.. Our ears are more finely tuned than we realize, and you can tell the difference when every single pulse of exhaust is in a single file line.

When @ssc_northamerica asks you to create a titanium exhaust for their record setting 295mph Tuatara Hypercar, utilizing your proprietary Z-pipe exhaust technology, and to shoehorn it into a minimal space, make sure you bring your A game!  I think I may have nailed this one 👌🏼🤞🏼
All jokes aside, here are some photos showing the feather-light 3D printed exhaust tips actually welded on, which I designed as a part of this system.  They are only 1mm thick and have a perfectly calculated taper and exit hole size; this maximizes the Z-pipe’s scavenging abilities and subsequent HP gains, as well as keeping the exhaust note as crisp as possible!

BADD GT, the worlds fastest street car, is here at my new facility for some high performance upgrades!  @johnnybohmerracing recently set the world record for a street car at 310.8mph/500.1kph with this vehicle, and we are hoping to see an even faster run next time after passing through my hands!  This is just a progress video to show you all how it is coming along, still plenty left to do on this car.  It is here for a custom titanium Z-pipe exhaust, 4” stainless downpipes with flex bellows and vband outlets, as well as some very customized mesh grills and an upgrade to dual parachutes!  Also doing something quite cool with the wastegates, think LFA style tips.  This is a car where serviceability is a #1 priority, and it’s safe to say this car will be much easier to work on after I’m done with it than before.  This is saying a lot considering how much more is being jammed into the same space!  If you can’t make it easy to work on then you’ve only done half the job!  Stay tuned for updates on this one.
